<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section>
    <title>Fundamentals of Probability</title>

    <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-theoretical-probability">
        <title></title>
        <p>
    If an event E has <m>n(E)</m> equally likely outcomes and its sample space S has <m>n(S)</m> equally likely outcomes, the <alert>theoretical probability</alert> of event, <m>P(E)</m>, is
    <md>
    <mrow>P(E) = \frac{\text{number of outcomes in event } E}{\text{total number of outcomes in sample space}} = \frac{n(E)}{n(S)}</mrow>
  </md>
        </p>
    </assemblage>
<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A die is rolled. The set of equally likely outcomes is <m>\{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\}</m>. 
      Find the probability of rolling:
    </p>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>a 2</p></li>
        <li><p>a number less than 4</p></li>
        <li><p>a number greater than 7</p></li>
        <li><p>a number less than 7</p></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <ol>
        <li><p><m>P(2) = \frac{1}{6}</m></p></li>
        <li><p>The outcomes are <m>\{1, 2, 3\}</m>, so <m>P(\text{less than 4}) = \frac{3}{6} = \frac{1}{2}</m></p></li>
        <li><p>There are no such outcomes, so <m>P(\text{greater than 7}) = \frac{0}{6} = 0</m></p></li>
        <li><p>All outcomes are less than 7, so <m>P(\text{less than 7}) = \frac{6}{6} = 1</m></p></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>







</section>